	|1-6~.	Il canto XVII @e al punto mediano del ^Paradiso~.
Per evidenziarlo, il poeta lo dispone al centro di uno schema matematico
basato sul numero di versi, dal c. XI al c. XXIII. Cfr. J.  Logan,
"The Poet's Central Numbers", in ^Modern Language Notes~ 86, 1971,
pp. 95-98, il quale nota che lo schema rispecchia quello riscontrabile
nei canti centrali del ^Purgatorio~ e identificato da C. S. Singleton
(cfr. ^Purg~.  XVII, n. 70-72). La medesima argomentazione @e stata
poi svolta da G. Brugnoli, "^Paradiso~ XVII", in ^L'Alighieri~ 5, 1995,
pp. 47-58. "The idea underlying the whole of this Seventeeth Canto is
that Dante is here claiming his share in the martyrdom through which the
souls in this planet had passed. True, for full and perfect martyrdom, as
Aquinas says, the actual suffering of death for Christ may be necessary
[^ST~ II-II, q. 124, a. 4]. To Dante his exile was a living death. True
also, he had not fought like his ancestor against the heathen; but was
it easier warfare to struggle against his fellow-citizens?" (Carroll).

